          <!-- Conclusion -->
          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">The Steel Makes the Difference</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
              Concrete is strong in compression but weak in tension. That's where reinforcement comes in. 
              The steel carries tensile loads, controls cracking, and provides ductility. Without proper 
              reinforcement, concrete structures fail suddenly and catastrophically. With it, they warn 
              before failure and last generations.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
              OBC Part 9 requirements aren't arbitrary - they're based on decades of engineering experience 
              and failure analysis. The specified reinforcement is the minimum for safety. In practice, 
              adding a bit extra costs little but provides significant additional strength and crack control.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              At Toronto Concrete, we never compromise on reinforcement. Every footing gets its bars, every 
              wall its grid, every slab its mesh or rebar. We maintain proper cover, make full lap splices, 
              and add extra steel at stress points. It's not the cheapest way, but it's the only way to 
              build foundations that last.
            </p>
